		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2014"></a><br><code>sle2014/paper17</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2014</a> paper:</span><br><i>Dynamic Scope Discovery for Model Transformations</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/MārisJukšs.html">Māris Jukšs</a>, <a href="../profile/ClarkVerbrugge.html">Clark Verbrugge</a>, <a href="../profile/DánielVarró.html">Dániel Varró</a>, <a href="../profile/HansVangheluwe.html">Hans Vangheluwe</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-319-11245-9_17">10.1007/978-3-319-11245-9_17</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5f.html"><span class="tagM">T5F: Performance</span></a><ul><li> Its main aim is runtime performance optimization of graph pattern matching in model transformations.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3b.html"><span class="tagL">T3B: Transformation Languages</span></a><ul><li> The technique is embedded in a model transformation engine and targets transformation execution.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4d.html"><span class="tagL">T4D: Interpretation</span></a><ul><li> It operates at runtime by dynamically reducing the search space for rule application.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4g.html"><span class="tagL">T4G: AI-for-SLE</span></a><ul><li> It employs a Naive Bayes classifier and online learning to predict likely match candidates.
</li></ul></li></ul>
